commentText: I am working for a Swedish company and my reporting manager is a Swedish women who visit Bangalore once in every three months. Husband & wife relationship is like you cook for yourself & i for myself. Even at restaurants separate bills are given be it for husband & wife or group of friends. No concept of sharing. Depression among people is high. The current generations have become atheist. Many churches have converted to museums.  Every time she feels sad going back to her country. She likes to talk to people. Share her happiness & sorrows. But the culture over there is very very different. I personally know many people from IT background who has stayed abroad for 4-5 years, made some quick money and invested in one or two properties and permanently moved to back to India.  The beautiful landscape & buildings, cleanliness abroad looks good for few months. For me atleast at the end of the day living in village area is peaceful with our own caring people.

commentText: I am a hillbilly from the middle himalayan Bhadarwah Valley of Jammu and Kashmir. The lifestyle we have traditionally followed is similar to what you call challenging. I mean, stocking groceries, planning in anticipation of possible weather induced inhibitions etc is a normal with us. And we find such life really beautiful when it's white all around with absolute silence. European conditions suit me rather than the majorly dusty, hot and humid conditions of India. Suitability to conditions varies, and depends on where you come from. Overall, life in Europe amounts to living, and life in India is all about material struggle, direction less hustle and basic survival. BTW, you must do some more research on the social security, unemployment benefits and other aspects of life in Europe.

Owners wanted masters degree level people for entry level positions back then, at entry level pay.   They said jobs came back but they really meant that they increased the number of entry level jobs and waited until people were desperate enough to just take them. They traded unemployment for underemployment, where graduates need to have as many jobs as the Jamaicans from that old In Living Color comedy sketch.  Cut to today, and it's still like the wild west out there. Nothing substantial has changed for people not in the 1% in 25 years or more.

While we may be considered highly skilled and reliable workers back home, in Germany, you need to align with the local expectations â€” including soft skills, communication abilities, and especially fluency in German (ideally at the C1 level). German language certificates are not always necessary â€” what really matters is how well you can communicate during the interview. Also, based on my own experience and conversations with HR at my company, there is a common perception that many Indian candidates exaggerate or misrepresent their experience on their CVs, which creates mistrust.  Taking courses at German universities, even short-term Weiterbildung programs, can really help. commentText: Just one thing to add: childcare is not free in every German federal state.   The one thing that baffles me is that many are surprised that bureaucracy is in German (paperwork / administration  and so forth).  I am German and I have not only lived in Germany, but also in 2 other countries, but at no point have I ever expected to be accommodated in English or in German. The idea did not even occur in my mind. In fact I had learned the languages before going there and dedicated a lot of time and money to it so I could actually achieve a certificated C1 level for one country and a C2 for the other.  I don't think you absolutely need that I believe you will probably get by with a B2 level, but at the least you should have a B1 level.  It is one thing if you fled from another country, then you really have no chance to prepare for this, but if you actively choose a country, no matter which one, you absolutely do have the chance to prepare and you absolutely should!  Personally I believe that speaking the language also will let you have a completely different experience and make life, social interactions and everything so much easier. I would not underestimate the power of language.

commentText:
I'm an engineer from Romania working and living in Germany for more than 8 years now.
 When I came over I did so with a direct contract, though, I did invest time in learning the language at least to a B2 level when I considered looking for a job here. And, while I have 8 years here, my language skills are far from what I want them to be, so I still, periodically, do language courses.
 Since then, with COVID and the drop in German Automotive industry, my company closed but my CEO collected a few of us and started a new one. So, in my 8 years, I collected unemployment for only 1 month.
 Switching out of the Automotive industry (where my main experience was) took about 1.5 - 2 years of constant learning, interviewing and self-correcting.
 I had a lot of interviews where I got to the end stage of the process but it took time, attention to what I could improve after each interview and a significant amount of energy and research. So, work through it, I'm not saying its 100% going to happen, but chances for skilled workers, with German language skills (even poor ones), are quite good in my experience.
 As for German bureaucracy, I come from Romania :) Germany does have more bureaucracy but I find it's functional and quite efficient. The social and taxation systems would probably not work as well without it. However, I do think a lot is over-regulated here and this is consistent with the opinion of my German colleagues :).
 
 What feel is missing and is becoming problematic is digitalization and quality of services. Most, from state provided services (finance, medical, city offices), to private, service oriented, businesses like banks and telecommunication are outdated, overpriced and of mediocre quality.
 
 All in, Germany is, for me, a lot better than Romania, the caveat being: your family and long-time friends are now a long way away. This is not a small factor in your quality of life. There are a lot of things to improve, but this is as much a chance as an issue, since you can be part of improving some aspects and helping your adoptive country.

commentText: I moved to Bulgaria as a self-employed EU national. It's not at all like moving from California to Idaho; there is quite a process to go through. Incl. depositing 12x mininum local salary, buying private health insurance, etc. I had to apply for a Bulstat number, and to do that you are required to go through local lawyers/accountants. Good ones are hard to find and charge a lot; plus they love to unexpectedly up their fees by 20%-30% because "inflation."  The income tax I pay is 10% minus 4% flat expenses = 6%. Sounds fantastic. Except the mandatory social security contributions are â‚¬600 per month (regardless of whether youâ€™ve had any income during that month or not). In much wealthier Czech/Slovakia, those are about â‚¬200 per month. And if you are a day late with the payments, the government is already charging you interest/penalty.  Lastly, I bought a one-bedroom condo unit. A "management company" swooped in and started charging â‚¬700+ in annual maintenance fees. For that, they provide nothing. No service contract and no one as much as mops the floor  outside my apartment all year long. On top of that, they're now in court with another "management company." Depending on the outcome, I may have to pay the fees a second time, all over again.  1 liter of milk costs â‚¬1 in Austria, â‚¬0.69 in Slovakia. My local Billa sells it for â‚¬2.00 - local Bulgarian milk, mind you. A 100-mile taxi ride to the airport, in my old country, sets you back â‚¬80; here it's â‚¬150. And that's before the upcoming switch to euro in January 2026.  So that's a foreigner's life in Bulgaria. A safe, peaceful place, stunning flora, low taxes, Russian and English widely understood, a stone's throw to Greece... And also a lot of screwy stuff and strong-arm tactics.

commentText: As a european (German): as said in the video, you don't go to Europe because of low fees. You will pay a lot for the system (maybe there are some exceptions like Bulgaria). People with wealth are hit relatively hard (in terms of their wealth). But i definitely think the quality of life is great. I think a lot of people downplay the safety, cleanliness and services you can get. Now yes, you may find some more safe and clean places in Asia. But we have a good package too i would say. Things are always subjective. I can't really stand heat / above 24Â°c, i like cold weather. I can't imagine myself living in a permanent tropical climate. For other people this sounds like a dream. So maybe Finland or Iceland would be more suitable to me and Malaysia or Oman to someone else. It'll be hard to find vegan food in Asia, in most of Europe that's pretty easy. Not many people will care about this but personally i do. It all has its ups and downs. If you are poor it's "great" (in quotes of course - being poor is obviously never great, but relatively speaking in comparison to other places). If you are so rich that you hardly care about the taxes and fees you gotta pay it's great for the quality of life. If you are somewhere in between i can see the reservations to be honest. Of course we are not a country, so every country within Europe is its own thing, we just share a lot of values. Especially places that are close together geographically of course.

commentText: About bringing your spouse with you to EU countries, you mentioned Italy and Austria but I have dealt with both as I have both of those citizenships...  In Italy, yes, you can just bring your spouse.  He / She can get a 5 year spousal visa with no language requirements.  Then the spouse can upgrade to permanent residency.  Austria, on the other hand, requires your spouse to have an A1 German language certificate as a start to get a 1 year visa to stay with you.  If your spouse resists wanting to learn another language, this can make it harder to keep the family together.  (this situation only applies if your spouse is NOT an EU citizen otherwise they have the right of free movement without further language restrictions)  If I am not mistaken, when that visa comes up for renewal after only one year, the spouse has to up the skills to A2 German to show that "integration" is progressing.  Like Italy, at the 5 year mark, the spouse can go for permanent residency.  Separately but related to language...  If you come from the US, Austria will let you convert your driver's license to an Austrian one which will then be valid for driving in all of the EU.  Even if you started from scratch, Austria will let you take the classes in English or German.  However, Italy will only let you drive on your US license for 1 year.  Then you MUST start from scratch and go through Italian driver's education in Italian with no option to do it in English.  Just a couple of things to keep in mind.

commentText: I see this argument often that people migrate because theyâ€™re chasing freedom, or better values, or some philosophical dream of the West. I donâ€™t buy itâ€”not for most. Especially for people coming from poorer countries.  In reality, the majority of migration patterns make sense when you follow jobs or government welfare.  Take the U.S., Canada, Germany, or the UK. Why are they popular destinations? Not just because theyâ€™re â€œfreeâ€ countries, but because they offer either (a) better job markets in the Western version of capitalism, or (b) generous social systems. And yes, sometimes both.  Look at Sweden, Germany, or the Netherlandsâ€”countries with robust welfare states. A lot of migrants aim there because once youâ€™re in the system, thereâ€™s a safety net: housing, healthcare, education, etc. Itâ€™s not exactly about bootstrapping yourself up through entrepreneurship. Thing is it does not help those whom are native. If anything it puts more drain on their system.  Meanwhile, other migrants aim for places like the U.S. or Canada where itâ€™s more about economic opportunity and work visas, not free housing.  Then thereâ€™s the language and culture aspect. Migrating from the U.S. to the UK or Ireland? Totally makes sense. Thereâ€™s linguistic and cultural overlap. But U.S. to Bulgaria? Thatâ€™s way more rare. Just like a Bulgarian moving to China isnâ€™t exactly common either.  Why? Because if someone was purely chasing economic growth and opportunity, Chinaâ€”with its massive industrial expansion and growing middle classâ€”should be a hotspot. But itâ€™s not. Why? Because that person isnâ€™t necessarily chasing raw growth or capitalism. Theyâ€™re chasing a Western-style social system with free education, healthcare, housing benefits, and residency rights.  So itâ€™s less about â€œfreedomâ€ and more about which country hands out the better freebie deal.  If the average migrant was an entrepreneur at heart, theyâ€™d go where the frontier is wide openâ€”maybe parts of Asia, Africa, or even South America. But most donâ€™t. They head to where they can plug into an existing system and live decently, even if they donâ€™t become rich.  Not saying thatâ€™s wrong, just saying letâ€™s be honest about it and cut the BS.

commentText: There is no such thing as a dream job unless you are self employed in your home town with good income, surrounded by your grannies and nannies and eating home food every day sitting on the lap of your mother! Every job is a challenge and a compromise and the further you get out from your comfort home or country the more challenging it gets. That is where Indian youths who have been pampered at home fail abroad with social adjustment in a new society. They are home sick all the time. They should be concentrating on learning new language, new culture, new skills, seeing new places, experiencing the diversity and nature and even enjoying the quietness and lonliness filled with personal advancement. Glad that you pointed out many of these things here. Europe or any where else is definitely not a bed of roses. Nobody is waiting for you with open arms to give you a job, a home or a car. It is a healthy struggle here all the way minus nepotism, corruption, unequality and injustice which you are hopefully trying to get away from.
